<p>"House cleaning near me" gets 110,000 searches per month on Google. "Maid service near me" gets 49,500. "Deep cleaning service" gets 22,200. Every one of those searches represents a homeowner or business ready to pay $150 to $500 for a cleaning job. If your company does not show up, a competitor answers that call.</p>
<p>Most cleaning companies rely on word-of-mouth, Nextdoor posts, and flyers. All three generate leads. None of them scale predictably. SEO for cleaning companies builds a pipeline of inbound leads that runs 24/7 without ad spend. The companies ranking in the top 3 of the <a href="/glossary/local-pack/">local pack</a> capture 75% of all clicks. Everyone below splits the remaining 25%.</p>
<p>The problem is that most SEO advice targets tech companies. Cleaning is different. You serve specific zip codes. Your services vary from weekly house cleaning to one-time deep cleans. Your customers search differently for residential versus commercial jobs. Generic SEO guides miss all of that.</p>
<p>We have published 3,500+ blog posts across 70+ industries, including hundreds for home services and cleaning businesses. Our average SEO score is 92%. This guide covers everything we know about SEO for cleaning companies.</p>
<p>Here is what you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>How to dominate the local pack and Google Maps for cleaning searches</li>
<li>The exact keywords cleaning companies should target by service type</li>
<li>How to build service pages and city pages that rank and convert</li>
<li>Why reviews are a top-3 ranking factor and how to generate them consistently</li>
<li>The content strategy that turns your website into a lead machine</li>
<li>A 90-day action plan you can start this week</li>
</ul>
<h2>Why SEO Matters for Cleaning Companies</h2>
<p>Cleaning is one of the most searched home service categories on Google. The demand is constant. People move, seasons change, offices need maintenance, and homeowners want their time back. SEO captures that demand at the moment of highest intent.</p>
<p>Here is the math. A cleaning company spending $500 per month on SEO that generates 20 qualified leads per month has a cost per lead of $25. If 8 of those leads book recurring weekly cleanings at $150 per visit, that is $4,800 per month in recurring revenue from $500 in marketing. The customer lifetime value of a weekly cleaning client is $7,800 per year. One good SEO campaign pays for itself many times over.</p>
