</ul>
<p>For more on building links, see our guide on <a href="/blog/build-backlinks-for-blog/">building backlinks for blogs</a>.</p>
<h2>Technical SEO for Cleaning Websites</h2>
<p>Technical problems block everything else from working. A slow site, broken mobile layout, or missing schema means your content and reviews cannot do their job.</p>
<h3>Site Speed</h3>
<p>Cleaning company websites are often built on slow WordPress themes with large, uncompressed images. Compress every image. Use WebP format. Target under 3 seconds for full page load on mobile. Google's Core Web Vitals directly affect your rankings.</p>
<h3>Mobile Optimization</h3>
<p>Over 60% of cleaning searches happen on mobile devices. Someone searching "house cleaning near me" while scrolling their phone needs to see your number, reviews, and booking button within 2 seconds of landing on your site. Test every page on a phone.</p>
<p>Key mobile checks:</p>
<ul>
<li>Phone number is tap-to-call</li>
<li>Booking form works on mobile screens</li>
<li>Text is readable without zooming</li>
<li>Buttons are large enough to tap (44px minimum)</li>
<li>No horizontal scrolling</li>
</ul>
<h3>Schema Markup</h3>
<p>Add <a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">schema markup</a> so Google understands your business:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>LocalBusiness</strong> schema with name, address, phone, hours, and service areas</li>
<li><strong>Service</strong> schema for each cleaning service page</li>
<li><strong>Review</strong> schema to show star ratings in search results</li>
<li><strong>FAQ</strong> schema on pages with frequently asked questions</li>
</ul>
<p>Schema earns rich snippets in search results. A listing with star ratings and pricing gets more clicks than plain text.</p>
